                <p><name type="person" key="1137"><hi rend="initialcap">F</hi>REYBERT, <hi
                            rend="initialcap">A</hi>DAM</name>, Private, <name type="organization"
                        key="757">Co. B, 1st Maryland Cavalry</name>, aged 34 years. Compound
                    comminuted fracture of the left parietal bone by a blow from a sabre. <name
                        type="BATTLE" key="300">Brandy Station, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury"
                            when="1863-06-09">June 9th, 1863</date>. Admitted to <name type="hospital">First Division
                                Hospital</name>, <name type="place">Annapolis, Maryland</name>, <date type="admit" when="1863-06-21">June 21st</date>. Returned to duty <date type="duty" when="1864-04-21">April 21st, 1864</date>. On
                    the expiration of his term of service, he re-enlisted in the <name
                        type="organization" key="758">1st Regiment, 1st Army Corps</name>,
                    (<name type="organization">Hancock's Corps</name>.) in the spring of <date when="1865">1865</date>. On <date type="admit"
                        when="1865-07-18">July 18th, 1865</date>, he was treated at <name
                        type="hospital" key="175">Stanton Hospital</name>, Washington, for catarrh,
                    was furloughed, and then transferred to <name type="hospital" key="162"
                        >Douglas</name>, and thence to <name type="hospital" key="173">Harewood
                        Hospital</name>s, and finally discharged on surgeon's certificate of
                    disability, <date type="discharge" when="1866-02-21">February 21st, 1866</date>.
                    From the hospital records it appears that he suffered little or no inconvenience
                    from his head injury, and that he was probably an incorrigible malingerer.</p>
            
